82B-AEDB-BAC41B65ED80</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Alex</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Richard</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Balch</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG027234%2F1"><gtr:id>EB1681F5-E025-43B1-983A-8E773EB2DBE6</gtr:id><gtr:title>The impact of ideas in policy change on labour migration</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G027234/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This fellowship builds on Dr Balch's PhD which analysed the impacts of ideas and knowledge on labour migration policies in the UK and Spain. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This work addresses the observation that we often know very little about the flow of ideas, and what actually drives politicians and policymakers to make decisions about immigration - decisions that ultimately have far-reaching implications. Instead of denouncing policymaking as irrational, incompetent, or even racist, it asks what kinds of ideas and knowledge actually shape and frame policy. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Through the two case studies of the UK and Spain (two of the major labour importers within the EU) the results show why, when, how and where policy frames on labour migration shift and change. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The fellowship allows Dr Balch to take the next steps through publication and dissemination of research findings to user communities thus increasing its impact within these same groups. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Part of the fellowship includes an overseas institutional visit at the Center for Comparative Immigration Studies (CCIS) at UC San Diego which will allow Dr Balch to develop his research by adding extra depth to a comparative perspective on European policies through reference to policy developments in the US. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>69199</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This research developed new ways of thinking about immigration policymaking. In particular, how ideas and knowledge flow through policy communities to influence policy outputs and outcomes; the role of epistemic communities in furthering more liberal policies on immigration; the veracity of government claims regarding the centrality of 'evidence-based policymaking'; and explaining when, why and how policies on immigration change.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>These findings are of relevance to the policymaking community generally, and all those interested in influencing the policy process. They point to the difficulties in translating research into influence, and highlight the specific circumstances when such changes did take place in certain case studies (labour migration policy in the UK and Spain). They are therefore potentially useful for all those involved in policy-relevant research, and policymakers seeking to improve the quality of decision-making.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>E0838823-9D18-45AB-BB83-0D9549A1BCCA</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56cb23a6e840c4.74623617</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>24F7932D-D178-47E5-B00D-65C003C318DC</gtr:id><gtr:title>Economic Migration and the Politics of Hospitality in Spain: Ideas and Policy Change</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Politics &amp; Policy</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/cb694b3398c7b8a8d9b76d4650ee4e02"><gtr:id>cb694b3398c7b8a8d9b76d4650ee4e02</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>BALCH A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>56cb27bc6640d6.40036907</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4306D876-C17A-4FBE-8E4C-6038F2FD7CB3</gtr:id><gtr:title>Managing Labour Migration in Europe: Ideas, Knowledge and Policy Change</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/f199b7995f34a993027cc8a5665982bc"><gtr:id>f199b7995f34a993027cc8a5665982bc</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Balch Alex</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:isbn>9780719080722</gtr:isbn><gtr:outcomeId>56cb2697d12590.44607387</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E0C2A527-DF7F-4B37-9EFB-BDBFFEBAD164</gtr:id><gtr:title>Labour and Epistemic Communities: The Case of 'Managed Migration' in the UK</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>The British Journal of Politics and International Relations</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/ba03d707c3fe110b0b46a8ff915c2780"><gtr:id>ba03d707c3fe110b0b46a8ff915c2780</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Balch A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:dat